    <name>
				<text>1.4.1.12 Simplifying simple algebraic fractions</text>
		</name>
    <questiontext format="moodle_auto_format">
				<text><![CDATA[<p class="HELM_exercise">Exercise</p>
<p>Leave the expression in its most simplified form</p>
<ol class="HELM_parts_inline">
<li>\(\dfrac{{@a1@}z}{z}\)</li>
<li>\(\dfrac{{@a1^2@}z}{{@a1@}z}\)</li>
<li>\(\dfrac{{@a1@}}{{@a1^2@}z^2}\)</li>
<li>\(\dfrac{{@a1@}z}{{@a1^2@}z^2}\)</li>
</ol>
<p>When simplifying remember only common factors can be cancelled.</p>

<h4 class="HELM_solution">Solution</h4>
<ol class="HELM_parts">
<li>[[input:ans1]] [[validation:ans1]] [[feedback:prt1]]</li>
<li>[[input:ans2]] [[validation:ans2]] [[feedback:prt2]]</li>
<li>[[input:ans3]] [[validation:ans3]] [[feedback:prt3]]</li>
<li>[[input:ans4]] [[validation:ans4]] [[feedback:prt4]]</li>
</ol>]]></text>
		</questiontext>
    <generalfeedback format="moodle_auto_format">
				<text><![CDATA[<ol class="HELM_parts">
<li>In the expression \(\dfrac{{@a1@}z}{z}\), the term \(z\) is common to both the numerator and the denominator and hence we have:<p>\(\dfrac{{@a1@}z}{z} = \displaystyle{{@ta1@}}.\)</p>
</li>
<li>In the expression \(\dfrac{{@a1^2@}z}{{@a1@}z}\), the terms \(z\) and \({@a1@}\) are both common to the numerator and the denominator and hence we have:<p>\(\dfrac{{@a1^2@}z}{{@a1@}z} = \displaystyle{{@ta2@}}.\)</p>
</li>
<li>The expression \(\dfrac{{@a1@}}{{@a1^2@}z^2}\) has the common factor \({@a1@}\) in both the numerator and the denominator and hence we have:<p>\(\dfrac{{@a1@}}{{@a1^2@}z^2} = \displaystyle{{@ta3@}}.\)
</p></li>
<li>In the expression \(\dfrac{{@a1@}z}{{@a1^2@}z^2}\), \(z\) and \({@a1@}\) are both common to the numerator and the denominator and hence we have:<p>\(\dfrac{{@a1@}z}{{@a1^2@}z^2} = \displaystyle{{@ta4@}}.\)</p>
</li>
</ol>]]></text>
		</generalfeedback>
